      <text>The movement in the trees resolved into shapes— not one creature, several: rolling spheres like Scout but larger, maybe twice the size, their surfaces almost woven, like wicker basketballs. Three of them tumbled forward through the purple shadows, movements coordinated and purposeful.

Kira held still, heart pounding—more aliens—great.

Then the ground near her feet bulged.

She jumped back—or tried to. Her injured leg buckled and she caught herself against a tree trunk, gasping.

Something pushed up through the springy groundcover: a pale structure about five centimeters across, growing rapidly. Within seconds it reached twenty centimeters tall—a bulbous base tapering to a narrow opening at the top. The surface was smooth, waxy, cream-colored. Hollow.

It looked like a flute—or an ocarina—some kind of instrument.

Air moved through it. A soft whistling sound, musical and strange.

And then it spoke.

¶

The voice—warm, cheerful, lilting with woodwind tones—said, &quot;Welcome to our planet! We&#39;ve been expecting someone!&quot;

Kira&#39;s brain short-circuited.

The plant thing was *talking*.

&quot;What the—&quot;

Buddy—excited—said, &quot;I&#39;m receiving audible communication patterns in Standard! The acoustic structure is unlike anything I&#39;ve documented, but the linguistic content is—&quot;

Kira said, &quot;Buddy, I can hear it. It&#39;s talking.&quot;

&quot;Yes! Isn&#39;t it wonderful?&quot;

The fluting voice continued, pleased and utterly surreal— &quot;I&#39;m Holloway. I coordinate resource distribution in this sector. We&#39;d like to conduct a preliminary wellness assessment following your arrival incident.&quot;

Two more of the pale fruiting structures pushed up nearby; the same voice emerged from all three sources simultaneously.

Kira said, &quot;You can TALK?&quot;

&quot;Yes! We learned human communication from educational materials left by the previous visitor. It&#39;s very exciting to finally use it again.&quot;

The larger rolling plants gathered closer, observing. Scout bounced back into view between them, clearly pleased.

«Previous visitor?»

Kira&#39;s thoughts were moving through mud. They could talk—the plants could talk—but the way they talked—

Kira said slowly, &quot;Where did you say you learned?&quot;

Buddy&#39;s processing pause was almost audible. He said, &quot;Based on the terminology and phrasing patterns, I believe they may have learned Standard from human resources management documentation.&quot;

&quot;Oh no.&quot;

Holloway continued warmly, &quot;Now then—have you experienced any workplace incidents in the past twenty-four hours?&quot;</text>
