      <text>Kira gestured at the forest, at herself, at everything, then said:

&quot;Workplace— I _crashed_. My ship crashed.&quot;

&quot;Excellent, thank you for that detail. Please describe the nature of any injuries sustained during the incident.&quot;

This couldn&#39;t be real—shock, delirium from blood loss.

Kira pointed at her leg; the bandage was soaked through, dark with blood. She said:

&quot;Laceration—bleeding—It needs treatment. Now.&quot;

&quot;Estimated blood loss in milliliters?&quot;

&quot;I don&#39;t—what? A lot—too much. Can you help or not?&quot;

&quot;Of course we can help!&quot; The warmth in that fluting voice was genuine. &quot;We need to document the incident first per Safety Protocol Seven-point-Three. I&#39;m already growing medical assistance nearby—Remedy should have the antibacterial compound ready in approximately twenty minutes.&quot;

A new fruiting body sprouted a meter away, speaking with the same voice, and said:

&quot;The growth cycle has specific biological requirements, but I assure you treatment is being prepared.&quot;

Twenty minutes—while she bled.

¶

&quot;Could we maybe speed that up?&quot;

&quot;I&#39;m afraid the compound synthesis follows a fixed timeline.—Now, were you following proper safety procedures at the time of the incident?&quot;

Kira stared at the fluted opening and said:

&quot;I was crashing—there is no safety protocol for your ship getting shot and exploding.&quot;

&quot;All activities have associated safety protocols per section 2.1. I&#39;ll note: protocols unavailable due to emergency circumstances.&quot; —&quot;Equipment malfunction or external hostile force?&quot;

&quot;External! Something shot at us!&quot;

&quot;Workplace violence will require additional documentation.&quot;

Her leg _hurt_. The pain was a constant throb now, sharp whenever she shifted weight. She was bleeding through the bandage. And this plant—this _talking plant from HR_—wanted to file incident reports.

&quot;Can we please do this *AFTER* you treat the injury?&quot;

&quot;Medical intervention requires completed incident documentation per section 4.2. I understand this may feel frustrating, but proper protocols ensure optimal outcomes.&quot;

The larger rolling plants pressed surfaces together, communicating somehow. Scout bounced sympathetically nearby.

Holloway said, &quot;I&#39;ll need your employee identification number.&quot;

Kira answered, &quot;Employee—I don&#39;t *WORK* here—I&#39;m not an employee—I&#39;m a—a crash survivor!&quot;

&quot;Visitor status, noted. We&#39;ll use arrival timestamp as reference identifier.&quot; —&quot;Now, what were you doing immediately before the incident occurred?&quot;

Kira said through her teeth:

&quot;Flying—in space.&quot;

&quot;And then?&quot;

&quot;And then something hit us.&quot;

&quot;I see. And were you the primary operator of the vessel?&quot;

&quot;I was cargo specialist, but—&quot;

Buddy tried to help, saying:

&quot;Kira&#39;s injury severity suggests immediate medical intervention should take priority over—&quot;
